For examples, see the google sheet: `DataSpaceResearchDataSubmissions_2020-11-01_2020-08-05`

We'll need to create a new function to replace `HandleManager.getCanonicalForm(handle)` at `princeton-5/dspace-jspui/src/main/webapp/display-item.jsp#143`. DOI data exists currently in the list of item URIs. Our best bet is probably something along the lines of:

```python
# pseudocode
def HandleManager.getCitation(handle):
     item = Item.get_from_handle(handle)
     uris = item.get_uris()
     doi_uri = [uri for uri in uris if "doi.org" in uri][0]
     return doi_uri
```

comments.body: I'm having a tough time getting `/items` to work, it's just timing out for me.
We'll have to update the Alma client for this.
@tpendragon you mean alma-rb?

> @tpendragon you mean alma-rb?

Yes

Thanks for this @pmgreen. I tried searching for a user by primary identifier in the API console.  I found a user in Alma with a 'primary id' value populated, but the user didn't have any data in the "identifiers" tab. The API docs say that if you don't provide `user_id_type` then it will search all unique fields, but that didn't seen to work. When I used `user_id_type=PRIMARYIDENTIFIER` it told me I didn't have the right key. It seems like a key with user read/write permissions should work so I'm not sure what is going on there.

Seems like there are some things to work through just to get the API responding correctly once we start working on this issue.

@hackartisan I think `user_id_type=PRIMARYIDENTIFIER` isn't working right now because PRIMARYIDENTIFIER is not enabled as a user_id_type in our sandbox, and we can't toggle it to enabled with our admin user. It looks like ExL would have to enable it. [ExL docs](https://developers.exlibrisgroup.com/alma/integrations/user-management/) seem to suggest that we'll be able to configure this with migration, perhaps with the test migration available Jan 4? We may have to ask ExL unless @mzelesky or @kevinreiss know the answer.
